    title: "Lithium & Mood Stabilizers",
    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Lithium & Mood Stabilizers", content: "Lithium and mood stabilizers alter neuronal signaling to prevent the pathological mood cycling of bipolar disorder. Lithium's mechanism involves multiple intracellular targets: inhibition of inositol monophosphatase (depleting the phosphoinositide signaling cascade), inhibition of glycogen synthase kinase-3-beta (GSK-3-beta, a key enzyme in neuroplasticity and circadian rhythm regulation), modulation of glutamate neurotransmission, and enhancement of serotonergic activity. Valproic acid increases brain GABA levels by inhibiting GABA transaminase and enhancing GABA synthesis, while also modulating voltage-gated sodium channels and blocking histone deacetylase. Carbamazepine and lamotrigine primarily block voltage-gated sodium channels, stabilizing neuronal membranes and reducing excitatory neurotransmission. Each mood stabilizer carries specific monitoring requirements: lithium requires serum level monitoring (0.6-1.2 mEq/L), thyroid function (causes hypothyroidism), and renal function (causes nephrogenic DI and chronic tubulointerstitial nephritis); valproic acid requires liver function, CBC with platelets, and serum levels (50-125 mcg/mL); carbamazepine requires CBC (risk of aplastic anemia, agranulocytosis), liver function, and serum levels. The RN monitors therapeutic drug levels, assesses for toxicity (lithium: tremor, GI symptoms, confusion; valproic acid: hepatotoxicity, pancreatitis, thrombocytopenia), ensures adequate hydration and sodium intake for lithium patients, educates about drug interactions, and monitors for suicidality during mood episodes." },
